153–Afdød","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, England"},"nl":{"1170–":"1170–Overleden","1170–Male":"1170–Overleden","1173–Female":"1173–Overleden","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1150–Male":"1150–Overleden","1153–Female":"1153–Overleden","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, England"},"en":{"1170–":"1170–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1173–Female":"1173–Deceased","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1153–Female":"1153–Deceased","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Covert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey, of Norman origin): habitational name from the Norman hamlet of Couvert in Calvados or from some other locality similarly named from Old French <i>(le) covert</i> ‘the secret corner, refuge, or thicket’. Sussex surname forms with the definite article and no preposition are not nicknames from Old French <i>covert</i> ‘secret(ive)’, as has been suggested, but are either references to ‘Le Covert’ as the place of origin or represent the common Norman practice of substituting <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in surnames. This surname is now extinct in Britain.","Americanized form of an unidentified Dutch or German name, perhaps   Kofoed   or German   Gobert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coovert","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Couvert</b> or its Dutch form <b>Coevert</b>, see   Covert  ."]},{"name":"Kofoed","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Nanna.","Danish: from <i>ko</i> ‘cow’ + <i>fod</i> ‘foot’, hence a nickname for someone with a club foot or other deformity of the foot. Compare   Kofford  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Covert II was born in 1170, his father, Richard Covert III, was 20 and his mother, Mrs. Richard Covert, was 17. He married Jane of Broadbridge in 1190. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1170–":"1170–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1153–Female":"1153–Surnud","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, England"},"fi":{"1170–":"1170–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1153–Female":"1153–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, England"},"fr":{"1170–":"1170–Décédé","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1173–Female":"1173–Décédée","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1153–Female":"1153–Décédée","1190":"1190","1153":"1153","1173":"1173","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Chaldon, Surrey, England":"Chaldon, Surrey, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William Covert II est né en 1170, son père, Richard Covert III, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Richard Covert, avait 17 ans. Il a épousé Jane of Broadbridge en 1190. Ils ont e